ce:section.ce:para:
The major focus of recent work involving RE-CDs has been on the application of hybrid materials in various areas, such as multimodal nanoprobes for magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), computed tomography (CT), and fluorescence imaging (FI) [51], in vivo cell imaging [52], detection of chemical species harmful to the environment, drugs [53], heavy metals, ions [54], among others. In addition, the strong luminescent mechanisms of the hybrid material encourage new relevant research in the area: the up-conversion of bismuth oxychloride doped with ytterbium (Yb3

                        +
                     ) and erbium (Er3

                        +
                     ) ions employing carbon dot modification [55]; research involving doping with terbium and its application in the detection of anthrax biomarkers (dipicolinic acid) as effective and selective sensors [37]; fluorescent biosensors for the simultaneous detection of pathogenic bacteria and antibiotics, with the possibility of integration with artificial intelligence [56]; lubricant additives to improve tribological performance [57]; ultrasensitive detection of oxytetracycline (OTC) through a multicolored fluorescence nanoprobe using europium [38], among others.

For this reason, we suggest some pertinent points regarding carbon dots and rare earth on which future research could contemplate:

                           (i)

development of the synthesis of RE-CDs in a continuous flow to accelerate the scalability of the process and reduce the number of steps;


                           (ii)

investigating other green precursors as a carbon source so that they can be potential substitutes for commonly used synthetic chemical reagents;


                           (iii)

investigation of the composition of carbon precursors to propose a synthesis mechanism;


                           (iv)

application of artificial intelligence associated with the design of experiments to optimize the synthesis of RE-CDs;


                           (v)

investigate the potential of RE-CDs in pesticide detection and how the functional groups present in the hybrid material can positively interfere with detection.
